2022-09-16T20:46:11Z	#<stupidIdeaOfTheDay https://twtxt.net/search?tag=stupidIdeaOfTheDay> (based on one I found randomly on Reddit)‚Ä®‚Ä®To avoid using Static passwords + TOTPs (like Google Authenticator codes), have a dynamic Single-factor authentication:‚Ä®Sign the time (in blocks of 30 seconds like with TOTPS) with your private key, so you have passwords valid for 30-90 seconds. Allow at most 10 attempts every 30 seconds. Obviously, the server checks a valid signature with your registered public key.‚Ä®For this, you can use an extension for your password manager as you are already doing to manage your static passwords + your TOTPs.‚Ä®‚Ä®Similar to what Yubikey originally did. There are many weak points like Man in the middle, and phishing, and possible attacks over a known message, that were solved with WebAuthn, but it's a nice exercise to think about.‚Ä®Disclaimer: Don't roll your own crypto‚Ä®Disclaimer 2: Don't implement 1FA, if you can do 2FA or MFA =P
