2022-10-11T16:35:07Z	(#npkkadq) You can take a look at the library I'm using, here:‚Ä®https://eapl.mx/webauthn/_test/client.html‚Ä®‚Ä®And the implementation there:‚Ä®https://eapl.mx/twtxt/login.html‚Ä®‚Ä®What's missing in the examples is having an identity tied to your Auth device (Hardware token or OS service like Microsoft Hello, Apple Keychain, Android Fingerprint). The explanation is long, but the abstraction is there. Your identity and private certificates are held for you by some 'magic' device.
2022-10-11T17:52:35Z	(#npkkadq) @<xuu https://txt.sour.is/user/xuu/twtxt.txt> Well, it took me like 4 hours to set up, implement and test the PHP library, with all the setup combinations, devices and such.‚Ä® ![](https://twtxt.net/media/vHDDNhT4YdPQafPFb43SaM.png) ‚Ä®‚Ä®So I'll say that using a password with a simple function like https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.password-verify.php‚Ä®is much easier than a whole library requiring communication between the server, the browser and the auth device... There is a security reason for that (mainly to avoid phishing, which is something I like compared to other solutions like SQRL)‚Ä® ![](https://twtxt.net/media/wJu9oa2NhhL7UtZ6jbFv8H.png)
